Trigger - originally came with 'accutrigger' type system. I immediately discarded the trigger safety in the middle, and maxed it out on its lightest pull setting. Never measured, but feels like crispy <1lb. Safety - Like a Remington 700 right thumb safety setup. Pull is safe, push forward to fire.  Honest performance: In good days, 0.75-1 MOA. On really bad days, 2MOA. On average, this is a reliably 1.25" MOA rifle measured using 3 and 5-rounds (@ capacity) groups from the bench, sandbagged, if you do your part (scope zeroed, not loose, no flinch, etc.). Never shot from a rigid rest, so this is sort of 'practical' measure.   Favorite ammo:I used FGMM 168 & 175 grain, Hornady Match 168 to get 1.25" MOA average reliably, with unskilled shot like me. Most of the time, I use Federal 155 gr or 180 gr SP or other hunting rounds to get 1.5" MOA average. Remington premier green box ammo is fine too. If you RELOAD: 178 gr hornady a-max, CCI primer, go for SLOWER (whatever your powder is, use a little less of it), and seat bullet as close to o-give as possible - more consistent powder burn and gentler recoil. this strategy gave me 0.333" MOA with 5 shots consistently from cold barrel to hot in this stupid rifle. (POI moved slightly after several strings of 5s, but grouping is still very tight.)  Least favorite, factory ammo: Sig Sauer Match ammo (won't fire sometimes). Russian stuff (also won't fire occasionaly). Maybe primer is too hard.Shipping situation: Will not ship anywhere, don't ask.Transaction: Cash + PPT fee @ local FFL only. My favorite is SC Guns in Santa Clara on a slow Sunday. I'm willing to drive out within 20-30 minutes of Downtown San Jose. Beyond that is a bit too far. All sale is final.

title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch HK VP9 Gray M700009GYA5
postcontent: Heckler & Koch HK VP9 Gray M700009GYA5, two mags, HK sights, BNIB.Buy it online at www.copsgunshop.net.  All FFL rules and regs apply.  Buyer pays shipping or sales tax.  Sorry, no trades.   In development for more than four years, the VP9 is Heckler & Koch’s latest handgun and the first striker fired HK since the renowned P7 series pistols were introduced in the 1980s. Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK “light pull” trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun. HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset. The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break. The VP9 uses HK’s ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable backstraps and six side panels— accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistol’s grip also instinctively position an operator’s hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip. Although influenced by other HK models, the VP9 has all the hallmarks of the latest, state-of-the-art handgun. All controls are completely ambidextrous. Slide releases are present on both sides of the frame and the magazine release can be easily activated by left- or right-handed shooters. A new feature is HK’s patented charging supports — simple components that are mounted on each side of the rear of the slide and provide better gripping leverage for racking the slide rearward. The charging supports speed reloading and make operating the VP9 easier for shooters with reduced hand strength. The VP pistols uses the proven P30 steel magazine; 15 and 10-round capacity available. The VP9 has an extended Picatinny MIL-STD-1913 rail molded into its polymer frame for mounting lights and accessories. The rail has been tested and certified to handle mounted accessories up to 5.6 ounces. The VP9’s proprietary captive flat recoil spring helps reduce the recoil forces effecting the operator and the handgun, improving shooter control during rapid firing and prolonging component service life. HK’s famous cold hammer forged barrel — made from cannon grade steel — ensures long service life. Similar HK barrels on 9 mm P30 models have fired more than 90,000 rounds in endurance tests in 2010. The polygonal bore profile, with no traditional lands-and-grooves rifling, contributes to longer service life as well as a slight increase in muzzle velocity. The VP9’s machined steel slide is protected from corrosion and wear by HK’s hostile environment finish and all metal components, including springs and pins have superior metallurgy. VP pistols are made in Heckler & Koch’s Oberndorf factory in southwest Germany. The VP9 is well-suited for civilian sport shooting, security, military, and law enforcement use. Covered by Heckler & Koch’s limited lifetime warranty, the HK VP9 is a solid design engineered with the famous long-term durability that make HK products especially cost-effective when subjected to total life cycle cost analysis. New for 2016 are Flat Dark Earth (FDE) models, VPs with special colorants added to the frame during the molding process creating the tan/brown color scheme increasing used by military and security units. The frame’s color is indestructible, permanent and completely resistant to fading or chemical change.

title: For Sale:  CZ 85 Combat 9mm
postcontent: I am offering my CZ 85 Combat semiautomatic handgun for sale or possibly trade. This specific model went out of production in 2016. I ordered this pistol from the Fin, Feather, and Fur outfitters in Ashland, Ohio back in 2015. Aside from the ambidextrous safety AND slide release that makes the CZ-85 a true left-hand friendly pistol, the Combat submodel features a trigger overtravel screw, lack of a firing pin block safety and magazine brake, and an adjustable rear sight.   This pistol is startlingly accurate, and I've neither done nor paid for any aftermarket work to it. CZ Custom or Cajun could probably improve on the stock trigger, but it's pretty damned good by my estimation as it is.  The pistol will come to you with everything that came with it from the factory, plus one Mec-Gar 19-round extended magazine that is generally the only one I ever use. I also have a set of softer rubber grip panels off of an SP-01 that have more palm swell and fit my hands better than the hard plastic grips. Buyer will get both sets.I love this gun, but I picked up a P226 Legion last fall and it has become my go-to Wonder Nine.  I wouldn't call the 85c a unicorn, but they're not very common. I'm a very frequent shooter and again, I love this gun. It probably gets 1K rounds a year through it. The slide and frame black polycoat shows no wear or damage, and my pistols are always stored clean and well-lubricated.  The 85 Combat has a black coated barrel as opposed to other CZ pistols that sport a white stainless barrel, as such it does show some wear from the slide. I'm firm on my price. I travel to the Mansfield/Ashland area occasionally, I can bring the gun with me if you are in that area or between there and Columbus. All buyers must be age 21 or above with valid Ohio identification. Thanks for checking it out.
